35:56.483 --> 36:01.369
I can give you her phone number or her email, actually.

36:01.390 --> 36:02.431
We email.

36:04.293 --> 36:08.118
It's a great way to stay in touch with people.

36:09.119 --> 36:18.351
Is there something that characterizes Yale design or is there something that says this is a Yale book?

36:19.152 --> 36:22.056
It's funny you should ask that.

36:23.099 --> 36:24.241
I've never thought so.

36:24.521 --> 36:31.411
And certainly we have never tried to, you know, make them look as if they all belonged here.

36:34.855 --> 36:37.159
You know, we do such a variety of books.

36:37.259 --> 36:39.682
It just didn't seem appropriate for us.

36:41.244 --> 36:43.267
But we try to make them all look good.

36:43.347 --> 36:48.314
We try to make them all well-designed and easy to read.

36:49.456 --> 36:52.600
But other than that, I would have to say no in terms of the book.

36:53.288 --> 37:21.996
There is a university printer, though, who just this past week sent me his proposed guidelines for Yale design, which he mainly intends to be up for brochures and other sort of ephemera that the university publishes, will not apply to jackets.

37:22.145 --> 37:34.942
But, you know, I think maybe in our other printed pieces that we will, uh... So is there a particular type that you think is favored?

37:34.962 --> 37:35.783
By my department?

37:35.803 --> 37:36.164
Yeah.

37:36.464 --> 37:37.305
There are a few.

37:37.585 --> 37:40.109
There are a few fonts we all love.

37:40.129 --> 37:40.970
Like, for instance?

37:41.931 --> 37:44.114
Um... The Sands.

37:45.936 --> 37:46.197
Mm-hmm.

37:46.237 --> 37:46.597
The Sans.

37:47.398 --> 37:48.900
Uh... S-A-N-S.

37:49.401 --> 37:50.663
No D.

37:50.683 --> 37:50.903
Um...

37:53.903 --> 37:55.084
Uh, Galliard.

37:56.326 --> 38:00.551
G-A-L-L-I-A-R-D.

38:00.571 --> 38:10.704
Um, Torino has certainly been a big, T-O-R, T-O-R-I-N-O, has been a big, um, sort of display font.

38:10.724 --> 38:11.845
You don't use it for a text.

38:11.865 --> 38:22.358
Um, Futura as well, F-U-T-U-R-A, which is an old sans-serif font. You know what a sans-serif is?

38:24.295 --> 38:34.770
And who makes those choices, those decisions?

38:34.790 --> 38:35.190
The designers.

38:35.210 --> 38:35.791
The designers.

38:36.172 --> 38:38.415
Again, the freelancers that you send out to?

38:39.156 --> 38:40.298
Well, we have a staff here.

38:40.358 --> 38:41.319
There's five of us here.

38:41.980 --> 38:44.143
So you have a staff of five people?

38:44.163 --> 38:50.472
Well, five here and me.

38:50.722 --> 38:54.386
We do most of the designs here.

38:54.446 --> 38:56.688
And then the jackets, the other things you send out?

38:57.569 --> 38:58.310
Not necessarily.

38:58.350 --> 39:01.313
We do most of the jackets here, too.

39:01.353 --> 39:04.416
So you said you free— We freelance out a small proportion.

39:04.436 --> 39:05.677
A small proportion, okay.

39:05.697 --> 39:06.298
Yes, small.

39:07.279 --> 39:10.162
And so what kind of a book would you normally form out?

39:12.164 --> 39:15.868
One that I don't want to touch with a ten-foot pole.

39:16.102 --> 39:19.427
So we won't identify what books those are?

39:19.587 --> 39:27.880
Well, it would be sometimes a book that's especially difficult and we know is going to be really time-consuming.

39:29.582 --> 39:33.308
We might freelance out the text.

39:37.334 --> 39:44.505
Sometimes I work, well, for instance, on that Encyclopedia of New England jacket, you know, I will do a certain number of designs.

39:44.603 --> 39:48.947
And then I just, I can't look at it anymore.

39:49.868 --> 39:51.390
And then I'll send it out to somebody else.

39:51.950 --> 39:54.293
So let's just start, I use that as a case study.

39:54.333 --> 40:03.442
So what were some of the possibilities for that encyclopedia of New England that you liked but didn't, that you, that... Yeah, I think I probably threw them all out.

40:03.622 --> 40:04.463
I had a pile of them.

40:04.723 --> 40:13.412
Well, you know, I get input before I even start designing, especially on something like that, that everybody's sort of nervous about, and it's a big book for us.

40:14.067 --> 40:15.308
So some of the ideas.

40:15.348 --> 40:15.849
Let's see.

40:15.889 --> 40:18.271
There was white picket fences.

40:19.693 --> 40:21.394
I was interested.

40:21.454 --> 40:25.658
There were weather vanes.

40:26.419 --> 40:26.940
Oh, nice.

40:26.960 --> 40:27.340
Okay.

40:27.360 --> 40:28.541
All saying New England, right?

40:28.962 --> 40:29.302
Yeah.

40:29.422 --> 40:35.788
There was, you know, shutters, green shutters on a white house.

40:35.949 --> 40:41.374
There was trees.

40:43.295 --> 40:44.416
trees in full colors.

40:44.537 --> 40:45.798
I just like to say a full-age tree.

40:48.101 --> 40:54.409
So it's interesting, you go from artifactual to natural, so that something was human-made or a natural scene.

40:54.529 --> 40:54.970
Yes, yes.

40:56.352 --> 40:58.975
Because any of them can evoke New England, really.

40:59.536 --> 41:00.377
Sure.

41:00.397 --> 41:01.518
There was a red barn.

41:02.399 --> 41:06.985
There was a whole scene of a New England village, like a Grandma Moses painting.

41:07.626 --> 41:10.129
And everybody was pretty happy with that for a while.

41:13.130 --> 41:18.196
The freelancer also went through a number of iterations of this.

41:19.558 --> 41:22.181
This was a more painful jacket than most.

41:24.384 --> 41:26.887
There was, um, I had a lobster.

41:27.208 --> 41:28.369
I had a lobster on one.

41:31.754 --> 41:36.219
So the point is to have something that evokes New England, but it's not a cliché, I guess, as well?

41:36.480 --> 41:39.584
Well, yes, you'd hope for that, yeah.

41:39.604 --> 41:39.964
Yes.

41:40.180 --> 41:42.142
That's why I think the clams are great.

41:42.643 --> 41:43.263
I think so, too.

41:43.644 --> 41:48.128
Because it's just who expects to see a bush of clams or whatever on the check, you know?

41:48.148 --> 41:51.532
You expect to see a covered bridge or a... Right, a covered bridge.

41:51.552 --> 41:54.174
That was another idea, yeah.

41:54.234 --> 41:58.018
And all are beautiful to the shore, but not especially new.

41:58.038 --> 42:00.861
Right, and kind of cliched, yeah.

42:00.881 --> 42:08.449
Yeah, I hate to use that word, but, you know, when you think of the covered bridge and the foliage and the seashore or whatever, but the clams are great.

42:09.188 --> 42:13.252
Did you get a consensus on that?

42:13.793 --> 42:14.573
Immediate.

42:14.814 --> 42:17.076
Is there a eureka moment where you say that's it?

42:18.597 --> 42:19.058
Pretty much.

42:19.258 --> 42:20.860
Well, the freelancer sent him.

42:20.900 --> 42:21.681
I printed him out.

42:21.981 --> 42:24.744
He had a few different ones.

42:24.984 --> 42:28.688
And I pulled out the clams and I said, this is great.

42:29.529 --> 42:31.270
And I showed it to the group.

42:31.511 --> 42:33.172
There's a group who approves the jackets.

42:33.272 --> 42:35.955
And everybody loved the clams almost immediately.

42:37.133 --> 42:37.874
Interesting, huh?

42:38.194 --> 42:44.601
And here it is, because it is the latest in a series of very successful Yale books, these encyclopedias.

42:44.681 --> 42:45.602
Encyclopedias, yeah.

42:45.622 --> 42:49.125
Which have taken off in their own way, the New York one.

42:49.746 --> 42:50.227
Yeah.

42:50.287 --> 42:53.250
And a number of them are just fabulous books.

42:53.590 --> 42:54.771
Well, thanks.

42:54.791 --> 42:55.232
I love them.

42:55.312 --> 42:55.772
I have them all.

42:55.812 --> 42:56.693
Me too.

42:57.094 --> 42:57.454
Me too.

42:57.474 --> 43:00.317
I was so fascinated reading that New England encyclopedia.

43:00.377 --> 43:01.318
I was checking proofs.

43:01.418 --> 43:06.163
I just kept getting waylaid by the text.

43:06.564 --> 43:06.904
Yeah, good stuff.

43:07.137 --> 43:08.138
Where are you from?

43:08.399 --> 43:09.240
Albany, New York.

43:09.260 --> 43:11.643
Ah, you're a New York lady.

43:11.663 --> 43:11.763
Yeah.

43:11.783 --> 43:12.164
And you?

43:12.304 --> 43:12.805
Where are you from?

43:12.825 --> 43:14.207
Oh, I'm from Massachusetts.

43:14.227 --> 43:17.752
I've lived most of my life, except for, you know, periods of school.

43:17.772 --> 43:17.872
Yeah.

43:19.254 --> 43:20.736
And worked up there for newspapers.

43:20.776 --> 43:27.024
I've been writing books for 15 years now, and wishing I'd started it earlier.

43:27.185 --> 43:27.886
Really?

43:27.906 --> 43:28.226
Yeah.

43:28.246 --> 43:29.488
It's just been great.

43:29.508 --> 43:30.529
Oh, that's nice.

43:30.549 --> 43:34.815
And able to... Do you have, like, an amount of time every day that you spend writing, or...?

43:34.998 --> 43:36.948
What I'm writing, I'm writing all the time.

43:37.250 --> 43:38.255
Really?

43:38.275 --> 43:38.396
Yeah.

43:38.416 --> 43:40.587
I'm between books, like this Yale thing.

